Data Visualization

Practice

ggplot(data = arbuthnot, aes(x = year, y = girls)) +
  geom_point()

With ggplot(): * The first argument is always the name of the dataset you wish to use for plotting. * Next, you provide the variables from the dataset to be assigned to different aesthetic elements of the plot, such as the x and the y axes. * adding a + at the end of the line, to indicate that you are adding a layer * then specify the geometric object to be used to create the plot.

?ggplot provides documentation for a function

Example with geom_line()

ggplot(data = arbuthnot, aes(x = year, y = girls)) +
  geom_line()

Adding a new variable to the data frame

Add total column to data

arbuthnot <- arbuthnot %>%
  mutate(total = boys + girls)

Add boy to girl ratio column

arbuthnot <- arbuthnot %>%
  mutate(boy_to_girl_ratio = boys / girls)

Add boy ratio column

arbuthnot <- arbuthnot %>%
  mutate(boy_ratio = boys / total)

Exercise 5

Ratio shows Arbuthnot numbers were much smaller but magnitude are mildly similar

present <- present %>%
  mutate(total = boys + girls)
present <- present %>%
  mutate(total_ratio = arbuthnot$total[c(1:63)] / present$total[c(1:63)])
ggplot(data = present, aes(x = year, y = total_ratio)) +
  geom_line()

Exercise 6

Data shows somewhat similar results. Does show growth over time. However there were more stark declines within that growth.
